<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Geometry on BRAULT Kevin</title><link>https://braultkevin.fr/categories/geometry/</link><description>Recent content in Geometry on BRAULT Kevin</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Tue, 18 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://braultkevin.fr/categories/geometry/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Convergence of the perimeter of an inscribed regular polygon</title><link>https://braultkevin.fr/posts/convergence-of-the-perimeter-of-an-inscribed-regular-polygon/</link><pubDate>Tue, 18 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://braultkevin.fr/posts/convergence-of-the-perimeter-of-an-inscribed-regular-polygon/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Consider a &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.4306em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;-sided regular polygon inscribed in a circle of radius
&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;r&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;r&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.4306em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right:0.02778em;"&gt;r&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The summits of the polygon lie on the circle, and all sides
of the polygon are of equal length. The angle at the center of a
regular polygon is the angle formed by two consecutive rays of the
circle passing through the vertices of the polygon. Since the polygon
is regular, all these angles at the center are equal.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>